\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Homework 11
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Mark Petersen
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M\subset\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 be compact, orientable, embedded 2-manifold with the induced metric.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 cannot have 
\begin_inset Formula $K\leq0$
\end_inset

 everywhere.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 cannot have 
\begin_inset Formula $K\geq0$
\end_inset

 everywhere unless 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}\left(M\right)>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is compact, then it is complete as a metric space and geodesically complete.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p,q\in M$
\end_inset

 be points such that 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is at a maximum distance from 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\left(t\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Part 2) According to the Gauss-Bonnet Theorem 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{M}KdA=2\pi\mathcal{X}\left(M\right),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is the sectional curvature.
 We suppose directly that 
\begin_inset Formula $K\geq0$
\end_inset

 everywhere.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is compact and embedded in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

, there are no boundaries.
 This means 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 must have curvature and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $K\neq0$
\end_inset

 everywhere.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{M}KdA>0$
\end_inset

.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}\left(M\right)>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

